
 ✅ Definition of Bug Life Cycle

The Bug Life Cycle (also called Defect Life Cycle) is the journey of a bug from the time it is found until it is fixed and closed.

In simple words:

> It shows the different stages a defect goes through in a testing process.

---

 🔄 Stages of Bug Life Cycle

1. New
2. Assigned
3. Open
4. Fixed
5. Retest
6. Closed
7. Reopen (if issue still exists)

---

 🧠 Real-Time Analogy: 🏥 Hospital Patient Treatment

Think of a bug like a patient in a hospital.

---

 🟢 1️⃣ New → Patient Admitted

 Tester finds a defect.
 Reports it in tool (like Jira).
 Status = New

👉 Like a patient entering hospital and getting registered.

---

 🟢 2️⃣ Assigned → Doctor Assigned

 Test lead assigns bug to developer.

👉 Like hospital assigning a doctor to the patient.

---

 🟢 3️⃣ Open → Doctor Checking Patient

 Developer starts working on the bug.
 Status = Open

👉 Doctor begins treatment.

---

 🟢 4️⃣ Fixed → Treatment Done

 Developer fixes the issue.
 Status = Fixed

👉 Doctor says treatment completed.

---

 🟢 5️⃣ Retest → Nurse Checks Recovery

 Tester retests the application.

👉 Nurse checks if patient recovered properly.

---

 🟢 6️⃣ Closed → Patient Discharged

 If working fine, tester closes the bug.

👉 Patient is healthy and discharged.

---

 🔴 7️⃣ Reopen → Patient Still Sick

 If issue still exists.
 Tester reopens the bug.

👉 Patient still has symptoms → sent back to doctor.

---

 📊 Visual Flow

```
New → Assigned → Open → Fixed → Retest → Closed
                               ↓
                             Reopen
```

other bug statuses apart from basic ones.

 🔵 1️⃣ Rejected

 Developer says: "This is not a bug."
 Maybe it is expected behavior.

🧠 Example:
Tester reports → "Login page background color is blue."
Developer says → "Yes, it is designed that way."
Status → Rejected

---

 🟡 2️⃣ Duplicate

 Same bug already reported earlier.

🧠 Example:
Two testers report same login error.
Second bug marked as → Duplicate

---

 🟢 3️⃣ Deferred

 Bug is valid but will be fixed later.
 Not high priority for current release.

🧠 Example:
Minor spelling mistake in footer.
Release is urgent → fix postponed.
Status → Deferred

---

 🟣 4️⃣ Not Reproducible (Cannot Reproduce)

 Developer cannot reproduce the issue.

🧠 Example:
Bug happens only in tester’s system.
Developer tests → works fine.
Status → Not Reproducible

---
